If you&#x27;re asking about **how to use CSS in Obsidian** to **style your CAS tags** (or just tags in general), you absolutely can! Here&#x27;s how to create a custom CSS snippet that gives your tags visual clarity using colors or icons.

---

### üîß Step-by-Step: Add Custom CSS for Tags in Obsidian

1. **Enable Custom CSS Snippets** in Obsidian:
   - Go to **Settings ‚Üí Appearance ‚Üí CSS Snippets**.
   - Click **&quot;Open snippets folder&quot;**.
   - Create a new file there, like: `cas-tags.css`.

2. **Paste this example CSS inside:**

```css
/* === CAS Tag Styling === */

/* Context Tags */
.tag[href^=&quot;#context/&quot;] {
  background-color: #2b6cb0;
  color: white;
  border-radius: 5px;
  padding: 2px 6px;
  font-size: 0.9em;
}

/* Action Tags */
.tag[href^=&quot;#action/&quot;] {
  background-color: #38a169;
  color: white;
  border-radius: 5px;
  padding: 2px 6px;
  font-size: 0.9em;
}

/* Status Tags */
.tag[href^=&quot;#status/&quot;] {
  background-color: #d69e2e;
  color: black;
  border-radius: 5px;
  padding: 2px 6px;
  font-size: 0.9em;
}

/* Optional: Special formatting for DONE or HIGH PRIORITY */
.tag[href=&quot;#status/done&quot;] {
  background-color: #319795;
}

.tag[href=&quot;#status/high-priority&quot;] {
  background-color: #e53e3e;
  font-weight: bold;
}
```

3. **Save the file**, go back to Obsidian, and toggle the snippet ON under **Settings ‚Üí Appearance ‚Üí CSS Snippets**.

---

### üß† Bonus: Emojis in Tags (Optional Aesthetic)

Use emojis directly in the tag text when writing:

```markdown
#context/üß†-mental
#action/üß™-test-this
#status/‚úÖ-done
```

And tweak the CSS to match the emoji versions if needed.

